    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 1st with a lineup headlined by **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, who earns today\u2019s highest efficiency score of 70.56. Despite a suboptimal #8 spot in the order and a headwind factor, **Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits from a massive dynamic platoon edge against Gallen, making him a high-upside play for stolen base production\u2014our scarcest category. **Yordan Alvarez** remains a core anchor with a 67.35 rating; while he faces a southpaw in Bennett, his elite 0.436 xwOBA and favorable park factors outweigh the platoon disadvantage, solidifying his status as a must-start alongside **Kazuma Okamoto**, who draws a favorable matchup against the hittable Woods Richardson.\n\nThe depth of our roster creates difficult decisions, particularly with **Carson Benge** (58.95) and **Kyle Schwarber** (58.46) just missing the elite tier but remaining strong starts. The most interesting bench decision involved **Dillon Dingler**, who barely cleared the marginal threshold at 53.43; while his dynamic platoon advantage against Gore provided a floor, the strength of Gore\u2019s secondary offerings kept him from reaching the \"strong\" designation. We continue to monitor the status of **Trea Turner**, **Christian Yelich**, **Hyeseong Kim**, and **Colt Keith**, all of whom are currently unavailable, forcing us to lean heavily on the speed-first profile of **Caleb Durbin** and the situational utility of **Junior Caminero**.\n\nRisk management remains critical as we navigate a slate featuring several dangerous opposing arms. **Jerar Encarnacion** faces a significant test against the high-velocity arsenal of McClanahan, resulting in a marginal 48.03 score that sits dangerously close to our floor; he remains in the lineup only due to a lack of better active alternatives on the bench. We are tracking the weather closely for **Pete Crow-Armstrong**, as the wind-in factor could suppress fly-ball distance, though his path to a multi-SB game remains the primary catalyst for his top-tier projection.",
